Affordable Housing Advisory Committee
Reviews the established policies and procedures, ordinances, land development regulations, etc., and recommends to Mayor and City Council specific initiatives to encourage or facilitate affordable housing.
Appearance Review Board
Reviews applications for certificates of appearance approval and make recommendations to Council on whether to approve, approve with conditions or deny such applications.
Audit Board
Advises City Council on financial and audit matters. Four members must have financial experience.
Board of Zoning Adjustment
Makes recommendations on certain special exceptions and variances to Orlando City Code Chapter 65 and appeals from determinations by the Zoning and Appearance Review Officials.
Building & Fire Codes Board of Appeal
Hears appeals from decisions by the Fire Chief and Building Official in resolving conflicts between the Building and Fire Prevention Codes.
Certification Appeals Board
Effective immediately, the Certification Review Board is suspended. This is to ensure the city is in compliance with federal law.
The city will provide updates when any further developments should occur.
Chapter 57 Review Board
Reviews complaints of racial, religious, gender and ethnic discrimination as well as appeals from denials of minority and women-owned business certification.
Civil Service Board
Administers and enforces the Civil Service Act and Code of Rules for firefighters and police officers; provides examinations, maintains eligibility lists, conducts investigations and rules on appeals for non-disciplinary matters.
Code Enforcement Board
Hears and decides alleged violations of codes and ordinances of the City.
Criminal Nuisance Abatement Board
Hears complaints of public nuisances on property where there is drug or prostitution related offenses, crimes at any pain-management clinic, dealing in stolen property, or gang activity. The Board also has the power to levy fines and request foreclosure, when appropriate.
Downtown Development Board
Works to revitalize and preserve property values, reduce present and prevent future deterioration, and encourage development in the district. Five members with principal residence, employment, place of business, or ownership of realty in the development area.
Downtown South Neighborhood Improvement District Advisory Council
Assists the Board of Directors in governing the affair of the district. Each member must own property in the district, represent a corporate owner of property within the district, or reside in the district.
Families, Parks & Recreation Advisory Board
Advises and assists Council in establishing city-wide comprehensive system of supervised recreational, cultural & educational facilities & programs; advises as to the proper care & management of facilities & charging rental fees for use of such facilities; establishes a comprehensive system of supervised recreation; considers City funding requests; enlists citizens' support.
Harry P. Leu Gardens Board of Trustees
Controls, operates, manages and maintains Harry P. Leu Gardens.
Historic Preservation Board
Promotes welfare of city through preservation and protection of historic structures, sites, monuments and areas. Recommends to City Council establishment of historic districts, designation of historic landmarks and holds public hearings.
Mennello Museum Board of Trustees
Advises the City on development, management and operation issues for the Mennello Museum of American Art.
Multi-Jurisdictional Advisory Boards
Municipal Planning Board
Local planning agency responsible for the Growth Management Program; prepares a comprehensive plan of municipal improvements; reviews plats; recommends zoning and other land development regulations; coordinates land development and regulatory functions of other City boards by consolidating recommendations to City Council.
Nominating Board
Recommends qualified individuals for appointments to City and Multi-jurisdictional boards. Recruits applicants with the interest, expertise and time for board service.
Other Boards and Committees
Other advisory boards including internal boards and town review committees.
Public Art Advisory Board
Establishes a Public Art Master Plan; recommends specific projects, selection of art works, landscaping and architectural enhancements.
Vehicle for Hire Appeal Board
Acts as an advisor to the Mayor & City Council on matters concerning the Vehicle for Hire industry and services; adopts rules and regulations to govern its operation and activities; hears appeals from an administrative decision or interpretation of the Vehicles for Hire Administrator.

Crime Prevention Tips
Follow these tips from the Orlando Police Department’s Neighborhood Watch Unit to ensure your safety.
Start a Neighborhood Watch Group
The Orlando Police Department trains neighborhood communities how to identify and report suspicious activities.
Request a Home Security Assessment
The Orlando Police Department offers free residential security assessments to its residents to educate homeowners on possible security measures.
Citizen Observer Program
The Citizen Observer Program (C.O.P) is comprised of volunteers who help police by patrolling neighborhoods, shopping malls and school zones. Their main purpose is to report suspicious activities, persons and vehicles. C.O.P. members have no law enforcement authority and carry no weapons.
False Alarm Reduction Program
The City of Orlando Alarm Ordinance was implemented in 1999 to address the growing number of false alarm activations. The Ordinance requires all active alarm systems to be registered with the Orlando Police Department.

Find Events
Looking for events permitted, hosted and sponsored by the City of Orlando? Orlando is a regional events capital, with hundreds of cultural, music and sports events happening throughout the year. View a listing of upcoming events.
Sports, Aquatics & Fitness
Would you like to be more active or play your favorite sport? The City of Orlando offers many different athletics and aquatics programs, from lessons to leagues.
Find Park and Recreation Activity Listings
Activities at city parks and recreation facilities including dance, nature, mentoring and field trips.
Youth Programs
View programs and activities available for youth and children provided by the City of Orlando.
Senior Connection
The City of Orlando’s Senior programs strive to provide quality recreational, educational and social programs to promote wellness and lifelong learning, while keeping seniors active and engaged in their community.
Volunteer for Orlando Cares
Want to give back to the City Beautiful? Apply for unique and rewarding volunteer opportunities in your community.
Get Involved in City Government
Become a neighborhood or community leader and get involved in your city
Public Safety Community Programs
Public safety community programs and volunteer opportunities offered by the Orlando Police Department and the Orlando Fire Department.
Educational Programs for Schools and Organizations
The city offers tours, demonstrations and other learning opportunities to educators and community organizations.
Pottery Studio
The Pottery Studio offers residents and visitors a safe and relaxing space to learn about and create pottery.
Find a Community Garden Near You
Community gardens are spaces for neighbors to come together and grow wholesome food for their families.
Request to Show Your Art in a City Gallery
The city offers three gallery spaces to expose artwork for regional artists.
Grant Funding Availability
Learn about funding opportunities offered by the City of Orlando, sign up for grant-related public meeting notices and connect to additional grant resources.
Celebrate Graduations
For our community, celebrating the thousands of students that will graduate is a symbol of hope and a reminder of the incredible potential that lies within our young people.

Reserve and Rent Space at a City Facility
Reserve space at a City facility or a City park for your event.
Request a Permit for a Large Outdoor Event
A Special Events Permit is required for any event on city property involving more than 100 people. Events with fewer than 100 people also require a Special Events permit if they involve vending, alcohol, temporary structures, or street closures.
Request a Free Speech Event Permit
If you'd like to host a rally in the City of Orlando, let us help you find a good location to share your message with others and guide you through the required permitting process of your event.
Request a Loudspeaker Permit
The City of Orlando requires permits for outdoor loudspeakers that are used on both private and public property in city limits.
Request a Block Party Permit
The City of Orlando requires permits for neighborhood parties that will impede a city roadway.
Request a Fireworks Permit
Do you want to use fireworks in a special event? The City of Orlando requires permits for fireworks displays in the city limits.
Request Approval for an Event with Alcohol on Private Property
If you are selling or catering alcoholic beverages, you will need a Zoning Official’s letter of determination before hosting your event.
Request Recognition from Mayor Buddy Dyer
Request a letter of recognition for milestone events, business anniversaries, and special honors.
Apply for Financial Assistance for Your Event
The Families, Parks and Recreation Advisory Board grant provides up to $1,800 for local nonprofit organization that want to hold events within the city limits.
